# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: spf-email
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:spf-email/bounce-address] A **bounce address** is an email address to which bounce messages are delivered.
[src:spf-email/bounce-address] There are many variants of the name, none of them used universally, including **return path**, **reverse path**, **envelope from**, **envelope sender**, **MAIL FROM**, **5321-FROM**, **return address**, **From_**, **Errors-to**, etc.
[src:spf-email/bounce-address] It is not uncommon for a single document to use several of these names.
[src:spf-email/bounce-address] All of these names refer to the email address provided with the `MAIL FROM` command during the SMTP session.
[src:spf-email/bounce-address] Ordinarily, the bounce address is not seen by email users and, without standardization of the name, it may cause confusion.
[src:spf-email/bounce-address] However, the envelope in this analogy is the contents of the `MAIL FROM` and `RCPT TO` fields from the SMTP session - and neither of these is normally visible to the user.
[src:spf-email/bounce-address] While it is most common for the `To:` and `From:` information in the letter to be the same as the "envelope" values, such is not always the case.
[src:spf-email/bounce-address] For example, on electronic mailing lists, the information seen in the "From:" header will come from the person who sent the email to the list, while the bounce address will be set to that of the mailing list software, so problems delivering the mailing list messages can be handled correctly.
[src:spf-email/bounce-address] Only the envelope information is looked at to resolve where the email should go; the body of the email is not examined.
[src:spf-email/bounce-address] Mail Transfer Agents (MTA) using the SMTP protocol use the `RCPT TO` command to determine where the email should go, and the `MAIL FROM` command to indicate where it came from.
[src:spf-email/bounce-address] While its original usage was to provide information about how to return bounce messages, since the late 1990s, other uses have come about.
[src:spf-email/bounce-address] Extended uses include mailing list handling in Variable envelope return path (VERP), email authentication via SPF, spam filtering, and backscatter reduction in Bounce Address Tag Validation.
[src:spf-email/bounce-address] The various terms have different origins and sometimes different meanings, although these differences have often become moot on the modern internet.
[src:spf-email/dmarc] Once the DMARC DNS entry is published, any receiving email server can authenticate the incoming email based on the instructions published by the domain owner within the DNS entry.
[src:spf-email/dmarc] If the email passes the authentication, it will be delivered and can be trusted.
[src:spf-email/dmarc] If the email fails the check, depending on the instructions held within the DMARC record the email could be delivered, quarantined or rejected.
[src:spf-email/dmarc] DMARC extends two existing email authentication mechanisms, Sender Policy Framework (SPF) and DomainKeys Identified Mail (DKIM).
[src:spf-email/dmarc] It allows the administrative owner of a domain to publish a policy in their DNS records to specify how to check the `From:` field presented to end users and how the receiver should deal with failures, and it provides a reporting mechanism for actions performed under those policies.
[src:spf-email/dmarc] DMARC is defined in the Internet Engineering Task Force's published document RFC 9989, dated May 2026, as "Standards Track".
[src:spf-email/dmarc] A DMARC policy allows a sender's domain to indicate that their email messages are protected by SPF and/or DKIM, and tells a receiver what to do if neither of those authentication methods passes – such as to reject the message or quarantine it.
[src:spf-email/dmarc] The policy can also specify how an email receiver can report back to the sender's domain about messages that pass and/or fail.
[src:spf-email/dmarc] These policies are published in the public Domain Name System (DNS) as text TXT records.
[src:spf-email/dmarc] DMARC does not directly address whether or not an email is spam or otherwise fraudulent.
[src:spf-email/dmarc] Instead, DMARC can require that a message not only pass DKIM or SPF validation, but that it also pass § Alignment.
[src:spf-email/dmarc] Under DMARC a message can fail even if it passes SPF or DKIM but fails alignment.
[src:spf-email/dmarc] Setting up DMARC may improve the deliverability of messages from legitimate senders.
[src:spf-email/dmarc] DMARC operates by checking that the domain in the message's `From:` field (also called "RFC5322.From") is "aligned" with other authenticated domain names.
[src:spf-email/dmarc] If either SPF (specified using the `aspf` field) or DKIM (specified using the `adkim` field) alignment checks pass, then the DMARC alignment test passes.
[src:spf-email/dmarc] Alignment may be specified as strict or relaxed.
[src:spf-email/dmarc] For strict alignment, the domain names must be identical.
[src:spf-email/dmarc] For relaxed alignment, the top-level "Organizational Domain" must match.
[src:spf-email/dmarc] The Organizational Domain used to be found by checking a list of public DNS suffixes.
[src:spf-email/dmarc] The upcoming spec instead specifies a Tree Walk through the parent domains.
[src:spf-email/dmarc] So, for example, "a.b.c.d.example.com.au" and "example.com.au" have the same Organizational Domain, because _dmarc.example.com.au is the only defined DMARC record among all the subdomains involved, including _dmarc.au.
[src:spf-email/dmarc] As this allows domain owners to define domain roles, it is deemed to be more accurate than the Public Suffix List.
[src:spf-email/dmarc] Like SPF and DKIM, DMARC uses the concept of a domain owner, the entity or entities authorized to make changes to a given DNS domain.
[src:spf-email/dmarc] SPF checks that the IP address of the sending server is authorized by the owner of the domain that appears in the SMTP `MAIL FROM` command.
[src:spf-email/dmarc] (The email address in MAIL FROM is also called the bounce address, envelope-from or RFC5321.MailFrom.) In addition to requiring that the SPF check passes, DMARC checks that RFC5321.MailFrom aligns with 5322.From.
[src:spf-email/dmarc] DKIM allows parts of an email message to be cryptographically signed, and the signature must cover the From field.
[src:spf-email/dmarc] Within the DKIM-Signature mail header, the `d=` (domain) and `s=` (selector) tags specify where in DNS to retrieve the public key for the signature.
[src:spf-email/dmarc] A valid signature proves that the signer is a domain owner, and that the From field hasn't been modified since the signature was applied.
[src:spf-email/dmarc] There may be several DKIM signatures on an email message; DMARC requires one valid signature where the domain in the `d=` tag aligns with the sender's domain stated in the `From:` header field.
[src:spf-email/dmarc] DMARC records are published in DNS with a subdomain label `_dmarc`, for example `_dmarc.example.com`.
[src:spf-email/dmarc] Compare this to SPF at `example.com`, and DKIM at `selector._domainkey.example.com`.
[src:spf-email/dmarc] The content of the TXT resource record consists of `name=value` tags, separated by semicolons, similar to SPF and DKIM.
[src:spf-email/dmarc] In this example, the entity controlling the example.com DNS domain intends to monitor SPF and/or DKIM failure rates and doesn't expect email to be sent from subdomains of example.com.
[src:spf-email/dmarc] Note that a subdomain can publish its own DMARC record; receivers must check it out before falling back to the organizational domain record.
[src:spf-email/dmarc] The protocol provides for various ratchets, or transitional states, to allow mail admins to gradually transition from not implementing DMARC at all, all the way through to an unyielding setup.
[src:spf-email/dmarc] The concept of stepwise adoption assumes that the goal of DMARC is the strongest setting, which is not the case for all domains.
[src:spf-email/dmarc] Regardless of intent, these mechanisms allow for greater flexibility.
[src:spf-email/dmarc] The policy published can be mitigated by applying it to only a percentage of the messages that fail DMARC check.
[src:spf-email/dmarc] Receivers are asked to select the given percentage of messages by a simple Bernoulli sampling algorithm.
[src:spf-email/dmarc] The rest of the messages should undergo the lower policy; that is, none if `p=quarantine`, quarantine if `p=reject`.
[src:spf-email/dmarc] If not specified, pct defaults to 100% of messages.
[src:spf-email/dmarc] The case `p=quarantine; pct=0;` is being used to force mailing list managers to rewrite the From: field, as some don't do so when `p=none`.
[src:spf-email/dmarc] Finally, the subdomain policy, `sp=` and the newly added no-domain policy, `np=` allow tweaking the policy for specific subdomains.
[src:spf-email/dmarc] DMARC is capable of producing two separate types of reports.
[src:spf-email/dmarc] Aggregate reports are sent to the address specified following the `rua`.
[src:spf-email/dmarc] Forensic reports are emailed to the address following the `ruf` tag.
[src:spf-email/dmarc] These mail addresses must be specified in URI mailto format (e.g. mailto:worker@example.net ).
[src:spf-email/dmarc] Multiple reporting addresses are valid and must each be in full URI format, separated by a comma.
[src:spf-email/dmarc] Target email addresses can belong to external domains.
[src:spf-email/dmarc] In that case, the target domain has to set up a DMARC record to say it agrees to receive them, otherwise it would be possible to exploit reporting for spam amplification.
[src:spf-email/dmarc] For example, say `receiver.example` receives a mail message `From: someone@sender.example` and wishes to report it.
[src:spf-email/dmarc] Aggregate Reports are sent as XML files, typically once per day.
[src:spf-email/dmarc] The subject mentions the "Report Domain", which indicates the DNS domain name about which the report was generated, and the "Submitter", which is the entity issuing the report.
[src:spf-email/dmarc] The XML content consists of a header, containing the policy on which the report is based and report metadata, followed by a number of records.
[src:spf-email/dmarc] Records can be put in a database as a relation and viewed in a tabular form.
[src:spf-email/dmarc] The XML schema is defined in Appendix C of specifications and a raw record is exemplified in dmarc.org.
[src:spf-email/dmarc] Here we stick with a relational example, which better conveys the nature of the data.
[src:spf-email/dmarc] DMARC records can also be directly transformed in HTML by applying an XSL stylesheet.
[src:spf-email/dmarc] Rows are grouped by source IP and authentication results, passing just the count of each group.
[src:spf-email/dmarc] The leftmost result columns, labelled **SPF** and **DKIM** show DMARC-wise results, either pass or fail, taking alignment into account.
[src:spf-email/dmarc] The rightmost ones, with similar labels, show the name of the domain which claims to participate in the sending of the message and (in parentheses) the authentication status of that claim according to the original protocol, SPF or DKIM, regardless of Identifier Alignment.
[src:spf-email/dmarc] On the right side, SPF can appear at most twice, once for the `Return-Path:` test and once for the `HELO` test; DKIM can appear once for each signature present in the message.
[src:spf-email/dmarc] In the example, the first row represents the main mail flow from example.org, and the second row is a DKIM glitch, such as signature breakage due to a minor alteration in transit.
[src:spf-email/dmarc] The third and fourth rows show typical failures modes of a forwarder and a mailing list, respectively.
[src:spf-email/dmarc] DMARC authentication failed for the last row only; it could have affected the message disposition if example.org had specified a strict policy.
[src:spf-email/dmarc] The **disposition** reflects the policy published actually applied to the messages, *none*, *quarantine*, or *reject*.
[src:spf-email/dmarc] Along with it, not shown in the table, DMARC provides for a policy override.
[src:spf-email/dmarc] if none of the above applies, a comment field allows to say more.
[src:spf-email/dmarc] Failure Reports, also known as Forensic Reports, are generated in real time and consist of possibly redacted copies of individual messages that failed SPF, DKIM or both based upon what value is specified in the `fo` tag.
[src:spf-email/dmarc] Their format, an extension of Abuse Reporting Format, resembles that of regular bounces in that they contain either a "message/rfc822" or a "text/rfc822-headers".
[src:spf-email/dmarc] There are several different types of email forwarding, some of which may break SPF.
[src:spf-email/dmarc] This is one of the reasons why email forwarding can affect DMARC authentication results.
[src:spf-email/dmarc] Mailing lists are a frequent cause of legitimate breakage of the original author's domain DKIM signature, for example by adding a prefix to the subject header.
[src:spf-email/dmarc] A number of workarounds are possible, and mailing list software packages are working on solutions.
[src:spf-email/dmarc] This workaround keeps the standard mailing list workflow, and is adopted by several large mailing list operators, but precludes the list adding footers and subject prefixes.
[src:spf-email/dmarc] This requires careful configuration of mailing software to make sure signed headers are not reordered or modified.
[src:spf-email/dmarc] A misconfigured email server may put List-id in its DKIM of messages sent to a mailing list, and then the list operator is forced to reject it or do From: rewriting.
[src:spf-email/dmarc] One of the most popular and least intrusive workarounds consists of rewriting the `From:` header field.
[src:spf-email/dmarc] The original author's address can then be added to the `Reply-To:` field.
[src:spf-email/dmarc] Rewriting can range from just appending `.INVALID` to the domain name, to allocating a temporary user ID where a modified version of the user's address is used, or an opaque ID is used, which keeps the user's "real" email address private from the list.
[src:spf-email/dmarc] In addition, the display name can be changed so as to show both the author and the list (or list operator).
[src:spf-email/dmarc] The last line, `Reply-To:`, has to be designed in order to accommodate reply-to-author functionality, in which case reply-to-list functionality is covered by the preceding change in the `From:` header field.
[src:spf-email/dmarc] That way, the original meaning of those fields is reversed.
[src:spf-email/dmarc] Altering the author is not fair in general, and can break the expected relationship between meaning and appearance of that datum.
[src:spf-email/dmarc] There are communities which use mailing lists to coordinate their work, and deploy tools which use the `From:` field to attribute authorship to attachments.
[src:spf-email/dmarc] Wrapping the message works nicely, for those who use an email client which understands wrapped messages.
[src:spf-email/dmarc] Not doing any change is perhaps the most obvious solution, except that they seem to be legally required in some countries, and that routinely losing SPF authentication may render overall authentication more fragile.
[src:spf-email/dmarc] The `Sender:` header is available to indicate that an email was sent on behalf of another party, but DMARC only checks policy for the From domain and ignores the Sender domain.
[src:spf-email/dmarc] Both ADSP and DMARC reject using the Sender field on the non-technical basis that many user agents do not display this to the recipient.
[src:spf-email/dmarc] A draft DMARC specification has been maintained since 30 January 2012.
[src:spf-email/dmarc] In October 2013, GNU Mailman 2.1.16 was released with options to handle posters from a domain with the DMARC policy of `p=reject`.
[src:spf-email/dmarc] The change tried to anticipate the interoperability issues expected in case restrictive policies were applied to domains with human users (as opposed to purely transactional mail domains).
[src:spf-email/dmarc] In April 2014, Yahoo changed its DMARC policy to `p=reject`, thereby causing misbehavior in several mailing lists.
[src:spf-email/dmarc] A few days later, AOL also changed its DMARC policy to `p=reject`.
[src:spf-email/dmarc] Those moves resulted in a significant amount of disruption, and those mailbox providers have been accused of forcing the costs of their own security failures onto third parties.
[src:spf-email/dmarc] As of 2020, the FAQ in the official DMARC wiki contains several suggestions for mailing lists to handle messages from a domain with a strict DMARC policy, of which the most widely implemented is the mailing list changing the “From” header to an address in its own domain.
[src:spf-email/dmarc] An IETF working group was formed in August 2014 in order to address DMARC issues, starting from interoperability concerns and possibly continuing with a revised standard specification and documentation.
[src:spf-email/dmarc] Meanwhile, the existing DMARC specification had reached an editorial state agreed upon and implemented by many.
[src:spf-email/dmarc] It was published in March 2015 on the Independent Submission stream in the "Informational" (non-standard) category as RFC 7489.
[src:spf-email/dmarc] In March 2017, the Federal Trade Commission published a study on DMARC usage by businesses.
[src:spf-email/dmarc] Out of 569 businesses, the study found about a third implemented any DMARC configuration, fewer than 10% used DMARC to instruct servers to reject unauthenticated messages, and a majority had implemented SPF.
[src:spf-email/dmarc] An updated RFC 9989 was published in May 2026.
[src:spf-email/dmarc] Popular services that perform DMARC analysis and/or record validation include Red Sift, Valimail, dmarcian, DMARC Advisor and EasyDmarc and Cloudflare.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] The **Domain Name System** (**DNS**) is a hierarchical and distributed name service that provides a naming system for computers, services, and other resources on the Internet or other Internet Protocol (IP) networks.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] It associates various information with *domain names* (identification strings) assigned to each of the associated entities.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] Most prominently, it translates readily memorized domain names to the numerical IP addresses needed for locating and identifying computer services and devices with the underlying network protocols.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] The Domain Name System has been an essential component of the functionality of the Internet since 1985.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] The Domain Name System delegates the responsibility of assigning domain names and mapping those names to Internet resources by designating authoritative name servers for each domain.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] Network administrators may delegate authority over subdomains of their allocated name space to other name servers.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] This mechanism provides distributed and fault-tolerant service and was designed to avoid a single large central database.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] In addition, the DNS specifies the technical functionality of the database service that is at its core.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] It defines the DNS protocol, a detailed specification of the data structures and data communication exchanges used in the DNS, as part of the Internet protocol suite.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] The Internet maintains two principal namespaces, the domain name hierarchy and the IP address spaces.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] The Domain Name System maintains the domain name hierarchy and provides translation services between it and the address spaces.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] Internet name servers and a communication protocol implement the Domain Name System.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] A DNS name server is a server that stores the DNS records for a domain; a DNS name server responds with answers to queries against its database.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] The most common types of records stored in the DNS database are for start of authority (SOA), IP addresses (A and AAAA), SMTP mail exchangers (MX), name servers (NS), pointers for reverse DNS lookups (PTR), and domain name aliases (CNAME).
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] Although not intended to be a general-purpose database, DNS has been expanded over time to store records for other types of data for either automatic lookups, such as DNSSEC records, or for human queries such as *responsible person* (RP) records.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] As a general-purpose database, the DNS has also been used in combating unsolicited email (spam) by storing blocklists.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] The DNS database is conventionally stored in a structured text file, the zone file, but other database systems are common.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] The Domain Name System originally used the User Datagram Protocol (UDP) as transport over IP.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] Reliability, security, and privacy concerns spawned the use of the Transmission Control Protocol (TCP) as well as numerous other protocol developments.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] An often-used analogy to explain the DNS is that it serves as the phone book for the Internet by translating human-friendly computer hostnames into IP addresses.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] The DNS can be quickly and transparently updated, allowing a service's location on the network to change without affecting the end users, who continue to use the same hostname.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] Users take advantage of this when they use meaningful Uniform Resource Locators (URLs) and e-mail addresses without having to know how the computer actually locates the services.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] An important and ubiquitous function of the DNS is its central role in distributed Internet services such as cloud services and content delivery networks.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] When a user accesses a distributed Internet service using a URL, the domain name of the URL is translated to the IP address of a server that is proximal to the user.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] The key functionality of the DNS exploited here is that different users can *simultaneously* receive different translations for the *same* domain name, a key point of divergence from a traditional phone-book view of the DNS.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] This process of using the DNS to assign proximal servers to users is key to providing faster and more reliable responses on the Internet and is widely used by most major Internet services.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] The DNS reflects the structure of administrative responsibility on the Internet.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] Each subdomain is a zone of administrative autonomy delegated to a manager.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] For zones operated by a registry, administrative information is often complemented by the registry's RDAP and WHOIS services.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] That data can be used to gain insight on, and track responsibility for, a given host on the Internet.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] Using a simpler, more memorable name in place of a host's numerical address dates back to the ARPANET era.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] The Stanford Research Institute (now SRI International) maintained a text file named HOSTS.TXT that mapped host names to the numerical addresses of computers on the ARPANET.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] Elizabeth Feinler developed and maintained the first ARPANET directory.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] Maintenance of numerical addresses, called the Assigned Numbers List, was handled by Jon Postel at the University of Southern California's Information Sciences Institute (ISI), whose team worked closely with SRI.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] Computers, including their hostnames and addresses, were added to the primary file by contacting the SRI Network Information Center (NIC), directed by Feinler, via telephone during business hours.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] Later, Feinler set up a WHOIS directory on a server in the NIC for retrieval of information about resources, contacts, and entities.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] She and her team developed the concept of domains.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] Feinler suggested that domains should be based on the location of the physical address of the computer.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] Computers at educational institutions would have the domain *edu*, for example.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] She and her team managed the Host Naming Registry from 1972 to 1989.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] By the early 1980s, maintaining a single, centralized host table had become slow and unwieldy and the emerging network required an automated naming system to address technical and personnel issues.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] Postel directed the task of forging a compromise between five competing proposals of solutions to Paul Mockapetris.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] Mockapetris instead created the Domain Name System in 1983 while at the University of Southern California.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] The Internet Engineering Task Force published the original specifications in RFC 882 and RFC 883 in November 1983.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] These were updated in RFC 973 in January 1986.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] In 1984, four UC Berkeley students, Douglas Terry, Mark Painter, David Riggle, and Songnian Zhou, wrote the first Unix name server implementation for the Berkeley Internet Name Domain, commonly referred to as BIND.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] In 1985, Kevin Dunlap of DEC substantially revised the DNS implementation.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] Mike Karels, Phil Almquist, and Paul Vixie then took over BIND maintenance.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] Internet Systems Consortium was founded in 1994 by Rick Adams, Paul Vixie, and Carl Malamud, expressly to provide a home for BIND development and maintenance.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] BIND versions from 4.9.3 onward were developed and maintained by ISC, with support provided by ISC's sponsors.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] As co-architects/programmers, Bob Halley and Paul Vixie released the first production-ready version of BIND version 8 in May 1997.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] Since 2000, over 43 different core developers have worked on BIND.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] In November 1987, RFC 1034 and RFC 1035 superseded the 1983 DNS specifications.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] Several additional Request for Comments have proposed extensions to the core DNS protocols.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] The domain name space consists of a tree data structure.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] Each node or leaf in the tree has a *label* and zero or more *resource records* (RR), which hold information associated with the domain name.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] The domain name itself consists of the label, concatenated with the name of its parent node on the right, separated by a dot.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] The tree sub-divides into *zones* beginning at the root zone.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] A DNS zone may consist of as many domains and subdomains as the zone manager chooses.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] DNS can also be partitioned according to *class* where the separate classes can be thought of as an array of parallel namespace trees.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] Administrative responsibility for any zone may be divided by creating additional zones.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] Authority over the new zone is said to be *delegated* to a designated name server.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] The parent zone ceases to be authoritative for the new zone.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] The definitive descriptions of the rules for forming domain names appear in RFC 1035, RFC 1123, RFC 2181, and RFC 5892.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] A domain name consists of one or more parts, technically called *labels*, that are conventionally concatenated, and delimited by dots, such as example.com.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] The right-most label conveys the top-level domain; for example, the domain name www.example.com belongs to the top-level domain *com*.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] The hierarchy of domains descends from right to left; each label to the left specifies a subdivision, or subdomain of the domain to the right.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] For example, the label *example* specifies a subdomain of the *com* domain, and *www* is a subdomain of example.com.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] This tree of subdivisions may have up to 127 levels.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] A label may contain zero to 63 characters, because the length is only allowed to take 6 bits.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] The null label of length zero is reserved for the root zone.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] The full domain name may not exceed the length of 253 characters in its textual representation (or 254 with the trailing dot).
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] In the internal binary representation of the DNS this maximum length of 253 requires 255 octets of storage, as it also stores the length of the first of many labels and adds last null byte.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] 255 length is only achieved with at least 6 labels (counting the last null label).
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] Although no technical limitation exists to prevent domain name labels from using any character that is representable by an octet, hostnames use a preferred format and character set.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] The characters allowed in labels are a subset of the ASCII character set, consisting of characters *a* through *z*, *A* through *Z*, digits *0* through *9*, and hyphen.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] This rule is known as the *LDH rule* (letters, digits, hyphen).
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] Domain names are interpreted in a case-independent manner.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] Labels may not start or end with a hyphen.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] An additional rule requires that top-level domain names should not be all-numeric.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] The limited set of ASCII characters permitted in the DNS prevented the representation of names and words of many languages in their native alphabets or scripts.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] To make this possible, ICANN approved the Internationalizing Domain Names in Applications (IDNA) system, by which user applications, such as web browsers, map Unicode strings into the valid DNS character set using Punycode.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] In 2009, ICANN approved the installation of internationalized domain name country code top-level domains (*ccTLD*s).
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] In addition, many registries of the existing top-level domain names (*TLD*s) have adopted the IDNA system, guided by RFC 5890, RFC 5891, RFC 5892, RFC 5893.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] The Domain Name System is maintained by a distributed database system, which uses the client–server model.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] The nodes of this database are the name servers.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] Each domain has at least one authoritative DNS server that publishes information about that domain and the name servers of any domains subordinate to it.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] The top of the hierarchy is served by the root name servers, the servers to query when looking up (*resolving*) a TLD.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] An authoritative name server can either be a *primary* server or a *secondary* server.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] Historically the terms *master/slave* and *primary/secondary* were sometimes used interchangeably but the current practice is to use the latter form.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] A primary server is a server that stores the original copies of all zone records.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] A secondary server uses a special automatic updating mechanism in the DNS protocol in communication with its primary to maintain an identical copy of the primary records.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] Every DNS zone must be assigned a set of authoritative name servers.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] This set of servers is stored in the parent domain zone with name server (NS) records.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] An authoritative server indicates its status of supplying definitive answers, deemed *authoritative*, by setting a protocol flag, called the "*Authoritative Answer*" (*AA*) bit in its responses.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] When a name server is designated as the authoritative server for a domain name for which it does not have authoritative data, it presents a type of error called a "lame delegation" or "lame response".
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] Domain name resolvers determine the domain name servers responsible for the domain name in question by a sequence of queries starting with the right-most (top-level) domain label.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] For proper operation of its domain name resolver, a network host is configured with an initial cache (*hints*) of the known addresses of the root name servers.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] The hints are updated periodically by an administrator by retrieving a dataset from a reliable source.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] Assuming the resolver has no cached records to accelerate the process, the resolution process starts with a query to one of the root servers.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] In typical operation, the root servers do not answer directly, but respond with a referral to more authoritative servers, e.g., a query for "www.wikipedia.org" is referred to the *org* servers.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] The resolver now queries the servers referred to, and iteratively repeats this process until it receives an authoritative answer.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] The diagram illustrates this process for the host that is named by the fully qualified domain name "www.wikipedia.org".
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] This mechanism would place a large traffic burden on the root servers, if every resolution on the Internet required starting at the root.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] In practice caching is used in DNS servers to off-load the root servers, and as a result, root name servers actually are involved in only a relatively small fraction of all requests.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] In theory, authoritative name servers are sufficient for the operation of the Internet.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] However, with only authoritative name servers operating, every DNS query must start with recursive queries at the root zone of the Domain Name System and each user system would have to implement resolver software capable of recursive operation.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] Typically, such caching DNS servers also implement the recursive algorithm necessary to resolve a given name starting with the DNS root through to the authoritative name servers of the queried domain.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] With this function implemented in the name server, user applications gain efficiency in design and operation.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] The combination of DNS caching and recursive functions in a name server is not mandatory; the functions can be implemented independently in servers for special purposes.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] Internet service providers (ISP) typically provide recursive and caching name servers for their customers.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] In addition, many home networking routers implement DNS caches and recursion to improve efficiency in the local network.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] The client side of the DNS is called a DNS resolver.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] A resolver is responsible for initiating and sequencing the queries that ultimately lead to a full resolution (translation) of the resource sought, e.g., translation of a domain name into an IP address.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] DNS resolvers are classified by a variety of query methods, such as *recursive*, *non-recursive*, and *iterative*.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] A resolution process may use a combination of these methods.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] In a *non-recursive query*, a DNS resolver queries a DNS server that provides a record either for which the server is authoritative, or it provides a partial result without querying other servers.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] In case of a caching DNS resolver, the non-recursive query of its local DNS cache delivers a result and reduces the load on upstream DNS servers by caching DNS resource records for a period of time after an initial response from upstream DNS servers.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] In a *recursive query*, a DNS resolver queries a single DNS server, which may in turn query other DNS servers on behalf of the requester.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] For example, a simple stub resolver running on a home router typically makes a recursive query to the DNS server run by the user's ISP.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] A recursive query is one for which the DNS server answers the query completely by querying other name servers as needed.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] In typical operation, a client issues a recursive query to a caching recursive DNS server, which subsequently issues non-recursive queries to determine the answer and send a single answer back to the client.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] The resolver, or another DNS server acting recursively on behalf of the resolver, negotiates use of recursive service using bits in the query headers.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] DNS servers are not required to support recursive queries.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] The *iterative query* procedure is a process in which a DNS resolver queries a chain of one or more DNS servers.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] Each server refers the client to the next server in the chain, until the current server can fully resolve the request.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] For example, a possible resolution of www.example.com would query a global root server, then a "com" server, and finally an "example.com" server.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] Name servers in delegations are identified by name, rather than by IP address.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] This means that a resolving name server must issue another DNS request to discover the IP address of the server to which it has been referred.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] If the name given in the delegation is a subdomain of the domain for which the delegation is being provided, there is a circular dependency.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] In this case, the name server providing the delegation must also provide one or more IP addresses for the authoritative name server mentioned in the delegation.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] The delegating name server provides this glue in the form of records in the *additional section* of the DNS response, and provides the delegation in the *authority section* of the response.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] A glue record is a combination of the name server and IP address.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] For example, if the authoritative name server for example.org is ns1.example.org, a computer trying to resolve www.example.org first resolves ns1.example.org.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] As ns1 is contained in example.org, this requires resolving example.org first, which presents a circular dependency.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] To break the dependency, the name server for the top level domain org includes glue along with the delegation for example.org.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] The glue records are address records that provide IP addresses for ns1.example.org.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] The resolver uses one or more of these IP addresses to query one of the domain's authoritative servers, which allows it to complete the DNS query.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] A common approach to reduce the query load on DNS servers is to cache the results of name resolution locally or on intermediary resolver hosts.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] Each DNS query result comes with a time to live (TTL), which indicates how long the information remains valid before it needs to be discarded or refreshed.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] This TTL is determined by the administrator of the authoritative DNS server and can range from a few seconds to several days or even weeks.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] As a result of this distributed caching architecture, changes to DNS records do not propagate throughout the network immediately, but require all caches to expire and to be refreshed after the TTL.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] RFC 1912 conveys basic rules for determining appropriate TTL values.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] Some resolvers may override TTL values, as the protocol supports caching for up to sixty-eight years or no caching at all.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] Negative caching, i.e. the caching of the fact of non-existence of a record, is determined by name servers authoritative for a zone which must include the Start of Authority (SOA) record when reporting no data of the requested type exists.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] The value of the *minimum* field of the SOA record and the TTL of the SOA itself is used to establish the TTL for the negative answer.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] A reverse DNS lookup is a query of the DNS for domain names when the IP address is known.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] Multiple domain names may be associated with an IP address.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] The DNS stores IP addresses in the form of domain names as specially formatted names in pointer (PTR) records within the infrastructure top-level domain arpa.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] For IPv6, the reverse lookup domain is ip6.arpa.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] The IP address is represented as a name in reverse-ordered octet representation for IPv4, and reverse-ordered nibble representation for IPv6.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] When performing a reverse lookup, the DNS client converts the address into these formats before querying the name for a PTR record following the delegation chain as for any DNS query.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] For example, assuming the IPv4 address 208.80.152.2 is assigned to Wikimedia, it is represented as a DNS name in reverse order: 2.152.80.208.in-addr.arpa.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] When the DNS resolver gets a pointer (PTR) request, it begins by querying the root servers, which point to the servers of American Registry for Internet Numbers (ARIN) for the 208.in-addr.arpa zone.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] ARIN's servers delegate 152.80.208.in-addr.arpa to Wikimedia to which the resolver sends another query for 2.152.80.208.in-addr.arpa, which results in an authoritative response.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] Users generally do not communicate directly with a DNS resolver.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] Instead DNS resolution takes place transparently in applications such as web browsers, e-mail clients, and other Internet applications.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] When an application makes a request that requires a domain name lookup, such programs send a resolution request to the DNS resolver in the local operating system, which in turn handles the communications required.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] The DNS resolver will almost invariably have a cache (see above) containing recent lookups.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] If the cache can provide the answer to the request, the resolver will return the value in the cache to the program that made the request.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] If the cache does not contain the answer, the resolver will send the request to one or more designated DNS servers.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] In any event, the name server thus queried will follow the process outlined above, until it either successfully finds a result or does not.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] It then returns its results to the DNS resolver; assuming it has found a result, the resolver duly caches that result for future use, and hands the result back to the software which initiated the request.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] Some large ISPs have configured their DNS servers to violate rules, such as by disobeying TTLs, or by indicating that a domain name does not exist just because one of its name servers does not respond.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] Some applications such as web browsers maintain an internal DNS cache to avoid repeated lookups via the network.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] This practice can add extra difficulty when debugging DNS issues as it obscures the history of such data.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] These caches typically use very short caching times on the order of one minute.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] Internet Explorer represents a notable exception: versions up to IE 3.x cache DNS records for 24 hours by default.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] Internet Explorer 4.x and later versions (up to IE 8) decrease the default timeout value to half an hour, which may be changed by modifying the default configuration.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] When Google Chrome detects issues with the DNS server it displays a specific error message.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] The Domain Name System includes several other functions and features.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] Hostnames and IP addresses are not required to match in a one-to-one relationship.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] Multiple hostnames may correspond to a single IP address, which is useful in virtual hosting, in which many web sites are served from a single host.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] Alternatively, a single hostname may resolve to many IP addresses to facilitate fault tolerance and load distribution to multiple server instances across an enterprise or the global Internet.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] DNS serves other purposes in addition to translating names to IP addresses.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] For instance, mail transfer agents use DNS to find the best mail server to deliver e-mail: An MX record provides a mapping between a domain and a mail exchanger; this can provide an additional layer of fault tolerance and load distribution.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] The DNS is used for efficient storage and distribution of IP addresses of block-listed email hosts.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] A common method is to place the IP address of the subject host into the sub-domain of a higher level domain name, and to resolve that name to a record that indicates a positive or a negative indication.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] E-mail servers can query blocklist.example to find out if a specific host connecting to them is in the block list.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] Many such block lists, either subscription-based or free of cost, are available for use by email administrators and anti-spam software.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] To provide resilience in the event of computer or network failure, multiple DNS servers are usually provided for coverage of each domain.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] At the top level of global DNS, thirteen groups of root name servers exist, with additional "copies" of them distributed worldwide via anycast addressing.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] Dynamic DNS (DDNS) updates a DNS server with a client IP address on-the-fly, for example, when moving between ISPs or mobile hot spots, or when the IP address changes administratively.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] The DNS protocol uses two types of DNS messages, queries and responses; both have the same format.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] Each message consists of a header and four sections: question, answer, authority, and an additional space.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] A header field (*flags*) controls the content of these four sections.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] The header section consists of the following fields: *Identification*, *Flags*, *Number of questions*, *Number of answers*, *Number of authority resource records* (RRs), and *Number of additional RRs*.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] Each field is 16 bits long, and appears in the order given.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] The identification field is used to match responses with queries.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] After the flags word, the header ends with four 16-bit integers which contain the number of records in each of the sections that follow, in the same order.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] Indicates if the message is a query (0) or a reply (1).
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] The type can be QUERY (standard query, 0), IQUERY (inverse query, 1), or STATUS (server status request, 2).
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] Authoritative Answer, in a response, indicates if the DNS server is authoritative for the queried hostname.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] TrunCation, indicates that this message was truncated due to excessive length.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] Recursion Desired, indicates if the client means a recursive query.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] Recursion Available, in a response, indicates if the replying DNS server supports recursion.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] Authentic Data, in a response, indicates if the replying DNS server verified the data.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] Checking Disabled, in a query, indicates that non-verified data is acceptable in a response.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] Response code, can be NOERROR (0), FORMERR (1, Format error), SERVFAIL (2), NXDOMAIN (3, Nonexistent domain), etc.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] The question section has a simpler format than the resource record format used in the other sections.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] The domain name is broken into discrete labels which are concatenated; each label is prefixed by the length of that label.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] The Domain Name System specifies a database of information elements for network resources.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] The types of information elements are categorized and organized with a list of DNS record types, the resource records (RRs).
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] Each record has a type (name and number), an expiration time (time to live), a class, and type-specific data.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] Resource records of the same type are described as a *resource record set* (RRset), having no special ordering.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] DNS resolvers return the entire set upon query, but servers may implement round-robin ordering to achieve load balancing.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] In contrast, the Domain Name System Security Extensions (DNSSEC) work on the complete set of resource record in canonical order.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] The *CLASS* of a record is set to IN (for *Internet*) for common DNS records involving Internet hostnames, servers, or IP addresses.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] In addition, the classes Chaos (CH) and Hesiod (HS) exist.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] Each class is an independent name space with potentially different delegations of DNS zones.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] In addition to resource records defined in a zone file, the domain name system also defines several request types that are used only in communication with other DNS nodes (*on the wire*), such as when performing zone transfers (AXFR/IXFR) or for EDNS (OPT).
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] The domain name system supports wildcard DNS records which specify names that start with the *asterisk label*, `*`, e.g., `*.example`.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] DNS records belonging to wildcard domain names specify rules for generating resource records within a single DNS zone by substituting whole labels with matching components of the query name, including any specified descendants.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] For example, in the following configuration, the DNS zone *x.example* specifies that all subdomains, including subdomains of subdomains, of *x.example* use the mail exchanger (MX) *a.x.example*.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] The AAAA record for *a.x.example* is needed to specify the mail exchanger IP address.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] As this has the result of excluding this domain name and its subdomains from the wildcard matches, an additional MX record for the subdomain *a.x.example*, as well as a wildcarded MX record for all of its subdomains, must also be defined in the DNS zone.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] The role of wildcard records was refined in RFC 4592, because the original definition in RFC 1034 was incomplete and resulted in misinterpretations by implementers.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] The original DNS protocol had limited provisions for extension with new features.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] In 1999, Paul Vixie published in RFC 2671 (superseded by RFC 6891) an extension mechanism, called Extension Mechanisms for DNS (EDNS) that introduced optional protocol elements without increasing overhead when not in use.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] This was accomplished through the OPT pseudo-resource record that only exists in wire transmissions of the protocol, but not in any zone files.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] Initial extensions were also suggested (EDNS0), such as increasing the DNS message size in UDP datagrams.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] Dynamic DNS updates use the UPDATE DNS opcode to add or remove resource records dynamically from a zone database maintained on an authoritative DNS server.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] This facility is useful to register network clients into the DNS when they boot or become otherwise available on the network.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] As a booting client may be assigned a different IP address each time from a DHCP server, it is not possible to provide static DNS assignments for such clients.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] From the time of its origin in 1983 the DNS has used the User Datagram Protocol (UDP) for transport over IP.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] Its limitations have motivated numerous protocol developments for reliability, security, privacy, and other criteria, in the following decades.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] UDP reserves port number 53 for servers listening to queries.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] Such a query consists of a clear-text request sent in a single UDP packet from the client, responded to with a clear-text reply sent in a single UDP packet from the server.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] When the length of the answer exceeds 512 bytes and both client and server support Extension Mechanisms for DNS (EDNS), larger UDP packets may be used.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] Use of DNS over UDP is limited by, among other things, its lack of transport-layer encryption, authentication, reliable delivery, and message length.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] In 1989, RFC 1123 specified optional Transmission Control Protocol (TCP) transport for DNS queries, replies and, particularly, zone transfers.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] Via fragmentation of long replies, TCP allows longer responses, reliable delivery, and re-use of long-lived connections between clients and servers.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] For larger responses, the server refers the client to TCP transport.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] DNS over TLS emerged as an IETF standard for encrypted DNS in 2016, utilizing Transport Layer Security (TLS) to protect the entire connection, rather than just the DNS payload.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] RFC 7858 specifies that opportunistic encryption and authenticated encryption may be supported, but did not make either server or client authentication mandatory.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] DNS over HTTPS was developed as a competing standard for DNS query transport in 2018, tunneling DNS query data over HTTPS, which transports HTTP over TLS.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] DoH was promoted as a more web-friendly alternative to DNS since, like DNSCrypt, it uses TCP port 443, and thus looks similar to web traffic, though they are easily differentiable in practice without proper padding.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] RFC 9250, published in 2022 by the Internet Engineering Task Force, describes DNS over QUIC.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] It has "privacy properties similar to DNS over TLS (DoT) [...], and latency characteristics similar to classic DNS over UDP".
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] This method is not the same as DNS over HTTP/3.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] RFC 9953, published in 2026 by the Internet Engineering Task Force, describes DNS over CoAP.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] The "application use case of DoC is inspired by DNS over HTTPS (DoH) (RFC 8484).
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] However, DoC aims for deployment in the constrained Internet of Things (IoT), which usually conflicts with the requirements introduced by HTTPS." DoC outperforms other DNS resolution mechanisms in constrained scenarios.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] Oblivious DNS (ODNS) was invented and implemented by researchers at Princeton University and the University of Chicago as an extension to unencrypted DNS, before DoH was standardized and widely deployed.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] Apple and Cloudflare subsequently deployed the technology in the context of DoH, as Oblivious DoH (ODoH).
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] ODoH combines ingress/egress separation (invented in ODNS) with DoH's HTTPS tunneling and TLS transport-layer encryption in a single protocol.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] DNS may be run over virtual private networks (VPNs) and tunneling protocols.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] The privacy gains of Oblivious DNS can be garnered through the use of the preexisting Tor network of ingress and egress nodes, paired with the transport-layer encryption provided by TLS.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] DNSCrypt uses either TCP port 443, the same port as HTTPS encrypted web traffic, or UDP port 443.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] This introduced not only privacy regarding the content of the query, but also a significant measure of firewall-traversal capability.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] Privacy of user/query pairs is created, since the ingress node does not know the content of the query, while the egress node does not know the identity of the client.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] DNSCrypt was first implemented in production by OpenDNS in December 2011.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] There are several free and open source software implementations that additionally integrate ODoH.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] It is available for a variety of operating systems, including Unix, Apple iOS, Linux, Android, and Windows.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] Originally, security concerns were not major design considerations for DNS software or any software for deployment on the early Internet, as the network was not open for participation by the general public.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] However, the expansion of the Internet into the commercial sector in the 1990s changed the requirements for security measures to protect data integrity and user authentication.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] Several vulnerability issues were discovered and exploited by malicious users.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] One such issue is DNS cache poisoning, in which data is distributed to caching resolvers under the pretense of being an authoritative origin server, thereby polluting the data store with potentially false information and long expiration times (time-to-live).
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] Subsequently, legitimate application requests may be redirected to network hosts operated with malicious intent.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] DNS responses traditionally do not have a cryptographic signature, leading to many attack possibilities; the Domain Name System Security Extensions (DNSSEC) modify DNS to add support for cryptographically signed responses.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] DNSCurve has been proposed as an alternative to DNSSEC.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] Other extensions, such as TSIG, add support for cryptographic authentication between trusted peers and are commonly used to authorize zone transfer or dynamic update operations.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] Techniques such as forward-confirmed reverse DNS can also be used to help validate DNS results.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] DNS can also "leak" from otherwise secure or private connections, if attention is not paid to their configuration, and at times DNS has been used to bypass firewalls by malicious persons, and exfiltrate data, since it is often seen as innocuous.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] Some domain names may be used to achieve spoofing effects.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] For example, paypal.com and paypa1.com are different names, yet users may be unable to distinguish them in a graphical user interface depending on the user's chosen typeface.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] In many fonts the letter *l* and the numeral *1* look very similar or even identical.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] This problem, known as the IDN homograph attack, is acute in systems that support internationalized domain names, as many character codes in ISO 10646 may appear identical on typical computer screens.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] This vulnerability is occasionally exploited in phishing.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] DNSMessenger is a type of cyber attack technique that uses the DNS to communicate and control malware remotely without relying on conventional protocols that might raise red flags.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] The DNSMessenger attack is covert because DNS is primarily used for domain name resolution and is often not closely monitored by network security tools, making it an effective channel for attackers to exploit.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] This technique involves the use of DNS TXT records to send commands to infected systems.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] Once malware has been surreptitiously installed on a victim's machine, it reaches out to a controlled domain to retrieve commands encoded in DNS text records.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] This form of malware communication is stealthy, as DNS requests are usually allowed through firewalls, and because DNS traffic is often seen as benign, these communications can bypass many network security defenses.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] DNSMessenger attacks can enable a wide array of malicious activities, from data exfiltration to the delivery of additional payloads, all while remaining under the radar of traditional network security measures.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] Understanding and defending against such methods are crucial for maintaining robust cybersecurity.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] Originally designed as a public, hierarchical, distributed and heavily cached database, the DNS protocol has no confidentiality controls.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] User queries and nameserver responses are sent unencrypted, enabling network packet sniffing, DNS hijacking, DNS cache poisoning and man-in-the-middle attacks.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] This deficiency is commonly used by cybercriminals and network operators for marketing purposes, user authentication on captive portals and censorship.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] User privacy is further exposed by proposals for increasing the level of client IP information in DNS queries (RFC 7871) for the benefit of content delivery networks.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] Solutions preventing DNS inspection by the local network operator have been criticized for thwarting corporate network security policies and Internet censorship.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] Public DNS servers are also criticized for contributing to the centralization of the Internet by placing control over DNS resolution in the hands of the few large companies which can afford to run public resolvers.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] The right to use a domain name is delegated by domain name registrars which are accredited by the Internet Corporation for Assigned Names and Numbers (ICANN) or other organizations such as OpenNIC, that are charged with overseeing the name and number systems of the Internet.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] In addition to ICANN, each top-level domain (TLD) is maintained and serviced technically by an administrative organization, operating a registry.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] A *registry* is responsible for operating the database of names within its authoritative zone, although the term is most often used for TLDs.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] A *registrant* is a person or organization who asked for domain registration.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] The registry receives registration information from each domain name *registrar*, which is authorized (accredited) to assign names in the corresponding zone and publishes the information using the WHOIS protocol.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] As of 2015, usage of RDAP is being considered.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] ICANN publishes the complete list of TLDs, TLD registries, and domain name registrars.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] Registrant information associated with domain names is maintained in an online database accessible with the WHOIS service.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] For most of the more than 290 country code top-level domains (ccTLDs), the domain registries maintain the WHOIS (Registrant, name servers, expiration dates, etc.) information.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] For instance, DENIC, Germany NIC, holds the DE domain data.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] From about 2001, most generic top-level domain (gTLD) registries have adopted this so-called *thick* registry approach, i.e. keeping the WHOIS data in central registries instead of registrar databases.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] For top-level domains on COM and NET, a *thin* registry model is used.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] The domain registry (GoDaddy, BigRock and PDR, VeriSign, etc.) holds basic WHOIS data (i.e., registrar and name servers, etc.).
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] On the other hand, organizations, i.e., registrants using ORG, are on the Public Interest Registry exclusively.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] Some domain name registries, often called *network information centers* (NIC), also function as registrars to end-users, in addition to providing access to the WHOIS datasets.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] The top-level domain registries, such as for the domains COM, NET, and ORG use a registry-registrar model consisting of many domain name registrars.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] In this method of management, the registry only manages the domain name database and the relationship with the registrars.
[src:spf-email/domain-name-system] The *registrants* (users of a domain name) are customers of the registrar, in some cases through additional subcontracting of resellers.
[src:spf-email/email-authentication] The original base of Internet email, Simple Mail Transfer Protocol (SMTP), has no such feature, so forged sender addresses in emails (a practice known as email spoofing) have been widely used in phishing, email spam, and various types of frauds.
[src:spf-email/email-authentication] To combat this, many competing email authentication proposals have been developed.
[src:spf-email/email-authentication] By 2018 three had been widely adopted – SPF, DKIM and DMARC.
[src:spf-email/email-authentication] The results of such validation can be used in automated email filtering, or can assist recipients when selecting an appropriate action.
[src:spf-email/email-authentication] This article does not cover user authentication of email submission and retrieval.
[src:spf-email/email-authentication] In the early 1980s, when Simple Mail Transfer Protocol (SMTP) was designed, it provided for no real verification of sending user or system.
[src:spf-email/email-authentication] This was not a problem while email systems were run by trusted corporations and universities, but since the commercialization of the Internet in the early 1990s, spam, phishing, and other crimes have been found to increasingly involve email.
[src:spf-email/email-authentication] Email authentication is a necessary first step towards identifying the origin of messages, and thereby making policies and laws more enforceable.
[src:spf-email/email-authentication] Hinging on domain ownership is a stance that emerged in the early 2000.
[src:spf-email/email-authentication] It implies a coarse-grained authentication, given that domains appear on the right part of email addresses, after the at sign.
[src:spf-email/email-authentication] Fine-grained authentication, at a user level, can be achieved by other means, such as Pretty Good Privacy and S/MIME.
[src:spf-email/email-authentication] At present, each individual must ultimately manage their own digital identity.
[src:spf-email/email-authentication] An outstanding rationale for email authentication is the ability to automate email filtering at receiving servers.
[src:spf-email/email-authentication] That way, spoofed messages can be rejected before they arrive to a user's inbox.
[src:spf-email/email-authentication] While protocols strive to devise ways to reliably block distrusted mail, security indicators can tag unauthenticated messages that still reach the inbox.
[src:spf-email/email-authentication] A 2018 study shows that security indicators can lower the click-through ratio by more than ten points: 48.9% to 37.2% of the users who open spoofed messages.
[src:spf-email/email-authentication] SMTP defines message *transport*, not the message *content*.
[src:spf-email/email-authentication] Thus, it defines the mail *envelope* and its parameters, such as the envelope sender, but not the header (except *trace information*) nor the body of the message itself.
[src:spf-email/email-authentication] STD 10 and RFC 5321 define SMTP (the envelope), while STD 11 and RFC 5322 define the message (header and body), formally referred to as the Internet Message Format.
[src:spf-email/email-authentication] A mail user agent (MUA) knows the *outgoing mail* SMTP server from its configuration.
[src:spf-email/email-authentication] An MTA (or a relay server) typically determines which server to connect to by looking up the MX (Mail eXchange) DNS resource record for each recipient's domain name.
[src:spf-email/email-authentication] The first few lines at the top of the header are usually trusted by the recipient.
[src:spf-email/email-authentication] Those lines are written by machines in the recipient's Administrative Management Domain (ADMD), which act upon their explicit mandate.
[src:spf-email/email-authentication] By contrast, the lines that prove the involvement of **A** and **B**, as well as of the purported author's MUA could be a counterfeit created by **C**.
[src:spf-email/email-authentication] The `Received:` field shown above is an epoch-making piece of the header.
[src:spf-email/email-authentication] The `Return-Path:` is written by **E**, the mail delivery agent (MDA), based on the message *envelope*.
[src:spf-email/email-authentication] Additional trace fields, designed for email authentication, can populate the top of the header.
[src:spf-email/email-authentication] Normally, messages sent out by an author's ADMD go directly to the destination's MX (that is **B → D** in the figures).
[src:spf-email/email-authentication] The sender's ADMD can add authentication tokens only if the message goes through its boxes.
[src:spf-email/email-authentication] Properly configured proxies appear as part of the author ADMD.
[src:spf-email/email-authentication] Some ADMDs block outbound connection to port 25 (SMTP) to avoid this.
[src:spf-email/email-authentication] This proactive technique is described in RFC 5068.
[src:spf-email/email-authentication] In addition, some block inbound SMTP connections from IPs listed as dialup/DSL/cable.
[src:spf-email/email-authentication] In this case the author's ADMD is not involved at all.
[src:spf-email/email-authentication] Some ISPs block port 587, although RFC 5068 clearly says: Access Providers MUST NOT block users from accessing the external Internet using the SUBMISSION port 587.
[src:spf-email/email-authentication] SPF allows the receiver to check that an email claimed to have come from a specific domain comes from an IP address authorized by that domain's administrators.
[src:spf-email/email-authentication] Usually, a domain administrator will authorize the IP addresses used by their own outbound MTAs, including any proxy or smarthost.
[src:spf-email/email-authentication] The IP address of the sending MTA is guaranteed to be valid by the Transmission Control Protocol, as it establishes the connection by checking that the remote host is reachable.
[src:spf-email/email-authentication] The receiving mail server receives the `HELO` SMTP command soon after the connection is set up, and a `Mail from:` at the beginning of each message.
[src:spf-email/email-authentication] The SPF verifier queries the Domain Name System (DNS) for a matching SPF record, which if it exists will specify the IP addresses authorized by that domain's administrator.
[src:spf-email/email-authentication] The result can be "pass", "fail", or some intermediate result - and systems will generally take this into account in their anti-spam filtering.
[src:spf-email/email-authentication] DKIM checks the *message content*, deploying digital signatures.
[src:spf-email/email-authentication] Rather than using digital certificates, the keys for signature-verification are distributed via the DNS.
[src:spf-email/email-authentication] That way, a message gets associated to a domain name.
[src:spf-email/email-authentication] A DKIM-compliant domain administrator generates one or more pairs of asymmetric keys, then hands private keys to the signing MTA, and publishes public keys on the DNS.
[src:spf-email/email-authentication] The DNS labels are structured as `*selector*._domainkey.example.com`, where *selector* identifies the key pair, and `_domainkey` is a fixed keyword, followed by the signing domain's name so that publication occurs under the authority of that domain's ADMD.
[src:spf-email/email-authentication] Just before injecting a message into the SMTP transport system, the signing MTA creates a digital signature that covers selected fields of the header and the body (or just its beginning).
[src:spf-email/email-authentication] The signature should cover substantive header fields such as `From:`, `To:`, `Date:`, and `Subject:`, and then is added to the message header itself, as a trace field.
[src:spf-email/email-authentication] Any number of relays can receive and forward the message and at every hop, the signature can be verified by retrieving the public key from the DNS.
[src:spf-email/email-authentication] As long as intermediate relays do not modify signed parts of a message, its DKIM-signatures remain valid.
[src:spf-email/email-authentication] DMARC allows the specification of a policy for authenticated messages.
[src:spf-email/email-authentication] It is built on top of two existing mechanisms, Sender Policy Framework (SPF) and DomainKeys Identified Mail (DKIM).
[src:spf-email/email-authentication] A range of other methods have been proposed, but are now either deprecated or have not yet gained widespread support.
[src:spf-email/email-authentication] ADSP allowed the specification of a policy for messages signed by the author's domain.
[src:spf-email/email-authentication] A message had to go through DKIM authentication first, then ADSP could demand a punishing treatment if the message was not signed by the author domain(s) —as per the `From:` header field.
[src:spf-email/email-authentication] ADSP was demoted to historic in November 2013.
[src:spf-email/email-authentication] VBR adds a vouch to an already authenticated identity.
[src:spf-email/email-authentication] This method requires some globally recognized authorities that certify the reputation of domains.
[src:spf-email/email-authentication] A sender can apply for a reference at a vouching authority.
[src:spf-email/email-authentication] The reference, if accepted, is published on the DNS branch managed by that authority.
[src:spf-email/email-authentication] A vouched sender should add a `VBR-Info:` header field to the messages it sends.
[src:spf-email/email-authentication] It should also add a DKIM signature, or use some other authentication method, such as SPF.
[src:spf-email/email-authentication] A receiver, after validating the sender's identity, can verify the vouch claimed in `VBR-Info:` by looking up the reference.
[src:spf-email/email-authentication] Applications should avoid using this method as a means of authentication.
[src:spf-email/email-authentication] Nevertheless, it is often carried out and its results, if any, written in the `Received:` header field besides the TCP information required by the SMTP specification.
[src:spf-email/email-authentication] The IP reverse, confirmed by looking up the IP address of the name just found, is just an indication that the IP was set up properly in the DNS.
[src:spf-email/email-authentication] The reverse resolution of a range of IP addresses can be delegated to the ADMD that uses them, or can remain managed by the network provider.
[src:spf-email/email-authentication] In the latter case, no useful identity related to the message can be obtained.
[src:spf-email/email-authentication] Looking up a DNSWL (DNS-based whitelist) may provide an assessment of the sender, possibly including its identification.
[src:spf-email/email-authentication] RFC 8601 defines a trace header field `Authentication-Results:` where a receiver can record the results of email authentication checks that it carried out.
[src:spf-email/email-authentication] Multiple results for multiple *methods* can be reported in the same field, separated by semicolons and wrapped as appropriate.
[src:spf-email/email-authentication] The first token after the field name, `receiver.example.org`, is the ID of the authentication server, a token known as an *authserv-id*.
[src:spf-email/email-authentication] A receiver supporting RFC 8601 is responsible to remove (or rename) any false header claiming to belong to its domain so that downstream filters cannot get confused.
[src:spf-email/email-authentication] However, those filters still need to be configured, as they have to know which identities the domain may use.
[src:spf-email/email-authentication] For a Mail User Agent (MUA), it is slightly harder to learn what identities it can trust.
[src:spf-email/email-authentication] Since users can receive email from multiple domains—e.g., if they have multiple email addresses -— any of those domains could let `Authentication-Results:` fields pass through because they looked neutral.
[src:spf-email/email-authentication] That way, a malicious sender can forge an *authserv-id* that the user would trust if the message arrived from a different domain.
[src:spf-email/email-authentication] A legitimate `Authentication-Results:` typically appears just above a `Received:` field by the same domain from which the message was relayed.
[src:spf-email/email-authentication] Additional `Received:` fields may appear between that and the top of the header, as the message got transferred internally between servers belonging to that same, trusted ADMD.
[src:spf-email/email-authentication] The Internet Assigned Numbers Authority maintains a registry of Email Authentication Parameters.
[src:spf-email/email-authentication] Not all parameters need to be registered, though.
[src:spf-email/email-authentication] For example, there can be local "policy" values designed for a site's internal use only, which correspond to local configuration and need no registration.
[src:spf-email/email-spoofing] The original transmission protocols used for email do not have built-in authentication methods: this deficiency allows spam and phishing emails to use spoofing in order to mislead the recipient.
[src:spf-email/email-spoofing] More recent countermeasures have made such spoofing from internet sources more difficult but they have not eliminated it completely; few internal networks have defences against a spoof email from a colleague's compromised computer on that network.
[src:spf-email/email-spoofing] Individuals and businesses deceived by spoof emails may suffer significant financial losses; in particular, spoofed emails are often used to infect computers with ransomware.
[src:spf-email/email-spoofing] Together, these are sometimes referred to as the "envelope" addressing – an analogy to a traditional paper envelope.
[src:spf-email/email-spoofing] The result is that the email recipient sees the email as having come from the address in the *From:* header.
[src:spf-email/email-spoofing] They may sometimes be able to find the *MAIL FROM* address, and if they reply to the email, it will go to either the address presented in the *From:* or *Reply-to:* header, but none of these addresses are typically reliable, so automated bounce messages may generate backscatter.
[src:spf-email/email-spoofing] Although email spoofing is effective in forging the email address, the IP address of the computer sending the mail can generally be identified from the "Received:" lines in the email header.
[src:spf-email/email-spoofing] In malicious cases, however, this is likely to be the computer of an innocent third party infected by malware that is sending the email without the owner's knowledge.
[src:spf-email/email-spoofing] Phishing and business email compromise scams generally involve an element of email spoofing.
[src:spf-email/email-spoofing] Email spoofing has been responsible for public incidents with serious business and financial consequences.
[src:spf-email/email-spoofing] This was the case in an October 2013 email to a news agency which was spoofed to look as if it was from the Swedish company Fingerprint Cards.
[src:spf-email/email-spoofing] The email stated that Samsung offered to purchase the company.
[src:spf-email/email-spoofing] The news spread and the company's stock price surged by 50%.
[src:spf-email/email-spoofing] Malware such as Klez and Sober among many more modern examples often search for email addresses within the computer they have infected, and they use those addresses both as targets for email, and also to create credible forged *From* fields in the emails that they send.
[src:spf-email/email-spoofing] This is to ensure that the emails are more likely to be opened.
[src:spf-email/email-spoofing] The worm code searches Alice's email address book and finds the addresses of Bob and Charlie.
[src:spf-email/email-spoofing] From Alice's computer, the worm sends an infected email to Bob, but is forged to appear as if it was sent by Charlie.
[src:spf-email/email-spoofing] In this case, even if Bob's system detects the incoming mail as containing malware, he sees the source as being Charlie, even though it really came from Alice's computer.
[src:spf-email/email-spoofing] Meanwhile, Alice may remain unaware that her computer has been infected, and Charlie does not know anything about it at all, unless he receives an error message from Bob.
[src:spf-email/email-spoofing] Traditionally, mail servers could accept a mail item, then later send a Non-Delivery Report or "bounce" message if it could not be delivered or had been quarantined for any reason.
[src:spf-email/email-spoofing] These would be sent to the "MAIL FROM:" a.k.a.
[src:spf-email/email-spoofing] With the massive rise in forged addresses, best practice is now to *not* generate NDRs for detected spam, viruses etc. but to reject the email during the SMTP transaction.
[src:spf-email/email-spoofing] When mail administrators fail to take this approach, their systems are guilty of sending "backscatter" emails to innocent parties – in itself a form of spam – or being used to perform "Joe job" attacks.
[src:spf-email/email-spoofing] The SSL/TLS system used to encrypt server-to-server email traffic can also be used to enforce authentication, but in practice it is seldom used, and a range of other potential solutions have also failed to gain traction.
[src:spf-email/email-spoofing] To effectively stop forged email being delivered, the sending domains, their mail servers, and the receiving system all need to be configured correctly for these higher standards of authentication.
[src:spf-email/email-spoofing] Although their use is increasing, estimates vary widely as to what percentage of emails have no form of domain authentication: from 8.6% to "almost half".
[src:spf-email/email-spoofing] For this reason, receiving mail systems typically have a range of settings to configure how they treat poorly-configured domains or email.
[src:spf-email/email-spoofing] While there has been research into improving email security, little emphasis has been placed on informing users whose email addresses have been used for spoofing.
[src:spf-email/email-spoofing] Currently, only the email recipient can identify a fake email, and users whose addresses are spoofed remain unaware unless the recipient manually scrutinizes the message or DMARC reporting is enabled.
[src:spf-email/email-spoofing] Typically, an attack targets specific employee roles within an organization by sending spoof emails that fraudulently represent a senior colleague, trusted customer, or supplier.
[src:spf-email/email-spoofing] (This type of attack is known as spear phishing).
[src:spf-email/email-spoofing] The email will issue instructions, such as approving payments or releasing client data.
[src:spf-email/email-spoofing] The emails often use social engineering to trick the victim into making money transfers to the bank account of the fraudster.
[src:spf-email/email-spoofing] The United States' Federal Bureau of Investigation recorded $26 billion of US and international losses associated with BEC attacks between June 2016 and July 2019.
[src:spf-email/email-spoofing] More recent figures estimate losses of over $50 billion from 2013 to 2022.
[src:spf-email/sender-policy-framework] The list of authorized sending hosts and IP addresses for a domain is published in the DNS records for that domain.
[src:spf-email/sender-policy-framework] Sender Policy Framework is defined in RFC 7208 dated April 2014 as a "proposed standard".
[src:spf-email/sender-policy-framework] The first public mention of the concept was in 2000 but went mostly unnoticed.
[src:spf-email/sender-policy-framework] No mention was made of the concept again until a first attempt at an SPF-like specification was published in 2002 on the IETF "namedroppers" mailing list by Dana Valerie Reese, who was unaware of the 2000 mention of the idea.
[src:spf-email/sender-policy-framework] The very next day, Paul Vixie posted his own SPF-like specification on the same list.
[src:spf-email/sender-policy-framework] These posts ignited a lot of interest, led to the forming of the IETF Anti-Spam Research Group (ASRG) and their mailing list, where the SPF idea was further developed.
[src:spf-email/sender-policy-framework] Among the proposals submitted to the ASRG were "Reverse MX" (RMX) by Hadmut Danisch, and "Designated Mailer Protocol" (DMP) by Gordon Fecyk.
[src:spf-email/sender-policy-framework] In June 2003, Meng Weng Wong merged the RMX and DMP specifications and solicited suggestions from others.
[src:spf-email/sender-policy-framework] Over the next six months, a large number of changes were made and a large community had started working on SPF.
[src:spf-email/sender-policy-framework] Originally SPF stood for *Sender Permitted From* and was sometimes also called *SMTP+SPF*; but its name was changed to *Sender Policy Framework* in February 2004.
[src:spf-email/sender-policy-framework] In early 2004, the IETF created the MARID working group and tried to use SPF and Microsoft's CallerID proposal as the basis for what is now known as Sender ID; but this collapsed due to technical and licensing conflicts.
[src:spf-email/sender-policy-framework] The SPF community returned to the original "classic" version of SPF.
[src:spf-email/sender-policy-framework] In July 2005, this version of the specification was approved by the IESG as an IETF *experiment*, inviting the community to observe SPF during the two years following publication.
[src:spf-email/sender-policy-framework] On April 28, 2006, the SPF RFC was published as experimental RFC 4408.
[src:spf-email/sender-policy-framework] On April 25, 2014 IETF published SPF in RFC 7208 as a "proposed standard" which "obsoleted" RFC 4408 and, as of May 2026, RFC 7208 had not been obsoleted.
[src:spf-email/sender-policy-framework] The Simple Mail Transfer Protocol permits any computer to send email claiming to be from any source address.
[src:spf-email/sender-policy-framework] This is exploited by spammers and scammers who often use forged email addresses, making it more difficult to trace a message back to its source, and easy for spammers to hide their identity in order to avoid responsibility.
[src:spf-email/sender-policy-framework] It is also used in phishing techniques, where users can be duped into disclosing private information in response to an email purportedly sent by an organization such as a bank.
[src:spf-email/sender-policy-framework] SPF allows the owner of an Internet domain to specify which computers are authorized to send mail with envelope-from addresses in that domain, using Domain Name System (DNS) records.
[src:spf-email/sender-policy-framework] Receivers verifying the SPF information in TXT records may reject messages from unauthorized sources before receiving the body of the message.
[src:spf-email/sender-policy-framework] Thus, the principles of operation are similar to those of DNS-based blackhole lists (DNSBL), except that SPF uses the authority delegation scheme of the Domain Name System.
[src:spf-email/sender-policy-framework] Current practice requires the use of TXT records, just as early implementations did.
[src:spf-email/sender-policy-framework] For a while a new record type (SPF, type 99) was registered and made available in common DNS software.
[src:spf-email/sender-policy-framework] Use of TXT records for SPF was intended as a transitional mechanism at the time.
[src:spf-email/sender-policy-framework] The experimental RFC, RFC 4408, section 3.1.1, suggested "an SPF-compliant domain name SHOULD have SPF records of both RR types".
[src:spf-email/sender-policy-framework] The proposed standard, RFC 7208, says "use of alternative DNS RR types was supported in SPF's experimental phase but has been discontinued".
[src:spf-email/sender-policy-framework] The envelope-from address is transmitted at the beginning of the SMTP dialog.
[src:spf-email/sender-policy-framework] If the server rejects the domain, the unauthorized client should receive a rejection message, and if that client was a relaying message transfer agent (MTA), a bounce message to the original envelope-from address may be generated.
[src:spf-email/sender-policy-framework] If the server accepts the domain, and subsequently also accepts the recipients and the body of the message, it should insert a Return-Path field in the message header in order to save the envelope-from address.
[src:spf-email/sender-policy-framework] While the address in the Return-Path often matches other originator addresses in the mail header such as the *header-from*, this is not necessarily the case, and SPF does not prevent forgery of these other addresses such as *sender* header.
[src:spf-email/sender-policy-framework] Spammers can send email with an SPF PASS result if they have an account in a domain with a sender policy, or abuse a compromised system in this domain.
[src:spf-email/sender-policy-framework] However, doing so makes the spammer easier to trace.
[src:spf-email/sender-policy-framework] SPF benefits owners of email addresses that are forged in the Return-Path.
[src:spf-email/sender-policy-framework] They receive large numbers of unsolicited error messages and other auto-replies.
[src:spf-email/sender-policy-framework] If such receivers use SPF to specify their legitimate source IP addresses and indicate FAIL result for all other addresses, receivers checking SPF can reject forgeries, thus reducing or eliminating the amount of backscatter.
[src:spf-email/sender-policy-framework] SPF has potential advantages beyond helping identify unwanted mail.
[src:spf-email/sender-policy-framework] In particular, if a sender provides SPF information, then receivers can use SPF PASS results in combination with an allow list to identify known reliable senders.
[src:spf-email/sender-policy-framework] Scenarios like compromised systems and shared sending mailers limit this use.
[src:spf-email/sender-policy-framework] If a domain publishes an SPF record, spammers and phishers are less likely to forge emails pretending to be from that domain, because the forged emails are more likely to be caught in spam filters which check the SPF record.
[src:spf-email/sender-policy-framework] Therefore, an SPF-protected domain is less attractive to spammers and phishers.
[src:spf-email/sender-policy-framework] Because an SPF-protected domain is less attractive as a spoofed address, it is less likely to be denylisted by spam filters and so ultimately the legitimate email from the domain is more likely to get through.
[src:spf-email/sender-policy-framework] The next hop does not allowlist the forwarder.
[src:spf-email/sender-policy-framework] This is a necessary and obvious feature of SPF – checks *behind* the "border" MTA (MX) of the receiver cannot work directly.
[src:spf-email/sender-policy-framework] Publishers of SPF FAIL policies must accept the risk of their legitimate emails being rejected or bounced.
[src:spf-email/sender-policy-framework] They should test (e.g., with a SOFTFAIL policy) until they are satisfied with the results.
[src:spf-email/sender-policy-framework] See below for a list of alternatives to plain message forwarding.
[src:spf-email/sender-policy-framework] For an empty Return-Path as used in error messages and other auto-replies, an SPF check of the HELO identity is mandatory.
[src:spf-email/sender-policy-framework] With a bogus HELO identity the result NONE would not help, but for valid host names SPF also protects the HELO identity.
[src:spf-email/sender-policy-framework] This SPF feature was always supported as an option for receivers, and later SPF drafts including the final specification recommend to check the HELO always.
[src:spf-email/sender-policy-framework] This allows receivers to allowlist sending mailers based on a HELO PASS, or to reject all mails after a HELO FAIL.
[src:spf-email/sender-policy-framework] It can also be used in reputation systems (any allow or deny list is a simple case of a reputation system).
[src:spf-email/sender-policy-framework] Thus, the key issue in SPF is the specification for the new DNS information that domains set and receivers use.
[src:spf-email/sender-policy-framework] The following words provide *mechanisms* to use to determine if a domain is eligible to send mail.
[src:spf-email/sender-policy-framework] The "ip4" and "a" specify the systems permitted to send messages for the given domain.
[src:spf-email/sender-policy-framework] The "-all" at the end specifies that, if the previous *mechanisms* did not match, the message should be rejected.
[src:spf-email/sender-policy-framework] The *modifiers* allow for future extensions to the framework.
[src:spf-email/sender-policy-framework] As soon as SPF implementations detect syntax errors in a sender policy they **must** abort the evaluation with result PERMERROR.
[src:spf-email/sender-policy-framework] Skipping erroneous *mechanisms* cannot work as expected, therefore `include:bad.example` and `redirect=bad.example` also cause a PERMERROR.
[src:spf-email/sender-policy-framework] Another safeguard is the maximum of ten mechanisms querying DNS, i.e. any mechanism except from IP4, IP6, and ALL.
[src:spf-email/sender-policy-framework] Implementations can abort the evaluation with result TEMPERROR when it takes too long or a DNS query times out or they can continue pretending that the query returned no data —which is called a "void lookup".
[src:spf-email/sender-policy-framework] However, they **must** return PERMERROR if the policy directly or indirectly needs more than ten queries for *mechanisms*.
[src:spf-email/sender-policy-framework] In addition, they **should** return PERMERROR as soon as more than two "void lookups" have been encountered.
[src:spf-email/sender-policy-framework] Any `redirect=` also counts towards this *processing limits*.
[src:spf-email/sender-policy-framework] A typical SPF HELO policy `v=spf1 a mx ip4:192.0.2.0 -all` may execute four or more DNS queries: (1) TXT record (SPF type was obsoleted by RFC 7208), (2) A or AAAA for mechanism `a`, (3) MX record and (4+) A or AAAA for each MX name, for mechanism `mx`.
[src:spf-email/sender-policy-framework] Except the first one, all those queries count towards the limit of 10.
[src:spf-email/sender-policy-framework] In addition if, for example, the sender has an IPv6 address, while its name and its two MX names have only IPv4 addresses, then the evaluation of the first two mechanisms already results in more than two void lookups and hence PERMERROR.
[src:spf-email/sender-policy-framework] Mechanisms `ip4`, `ip6` and `all` need no DNS lookup.
[src:spf-email/sender-policy-framework] To enable rapid testing and deployment, initial versions of SPF checked for its setting in the DNS TXT record of the sending domain - even though this record was traditionally supposed to be free-form text with no semantics attached.
[src:spf-email/sender-policy-framework] Although in July 2005, IANA assigned a specific Resource Record type 99 to SPF the uptake of was never high, and having two mechanisms was confusing for users.
[src:spf-email/sender-policy-framework] As SPF increasingly prevents spammers from spoofing the envelope-from address, many have moved to only spoof the address in the From field of the mail header, which is actually displayed to the recipient rather than only processed by the recipient's message transfer agent (MTA).
[src:spf-email/sender-policy-framework] SPF (or DKIM) can be used together with DMARC though, to also check the From field of the mail header.
[src:spf-email/sender-policy-framework] Custom proprietary implementations are required to protect against such display name spoofing and cannot utilize SPF.
[src:spf-email/sender-policy-framework] Anti-spam software such as SpamAssassin version 3.0.0 and ASSP implement SPF.
[src:spf-email/sender-policy-framework] Many mail transfer agents (MTAs) support SPF directly such as Courier, CommuniGate Pro, Wildcat, MDaemon, and Microsoft Exchange, or have patches or plug-ins available that support SPF, including Postfix, Sendmail, Exim, qmail, and Qpsmtpd.
[src:spf-email/sender-policy-framework] As of 2017, more than eight million domains publish SPF FAIL `-all` policies.
[src:spf-email/sender-policy-framework] In a survey published in 2007, 5% of the `.com` and `.net` domains had some kind of SPF policy.
[src:spf-email/sender-policy-framework] In 2009, a continuous survey run at Nokia Research reports that 51% of the tested domains specify an SPF policy.
[src:spf-email/sender-policy-framework] These results can include trivial policies like `v=spf1 ?all`.
[src:spf-email/sender-policy-framework] In April 2007, BITS, a division of the Financial Services Roundtable, published email security recommendations for its members including SPF deployment.
[src:spf-email/sender-policy-framework] In 2008, the Messaging Anti-Abuse Working Group (MAAWG) published a paper about email authentication covering SPF, Sender ID, and DomainKeys Identified Mail (DKIM).
[src:spf-email/sender-policy-framework] In their "Sender Best Communication Practices" the MAAWG stated: "At the very least, senders should incorporate SPF records for their mailing domains".
[src:spf-email/sender-policy-framework] In 2015, the Messaging Anti-Abuse Working Group (MAAWG) revised a paper about email authentication covering SPF, DomainKeys Identified Mail (DKIM), and DMARC (DMARC).
[src:spf-email/sender-policy-framework] In their revised "Sender Best Communication Practices" the MAAWG stated: "Authentication supports transparency by further identifying the sender(s) of a message, while also contributing to the reduction or elimination of spoofed and forged addresses".
[src:spf-email/sender-policy-framework] From February 1, 2024, Google requires SPF or DKIM for all domains sending emails to Gmail accounts.
[src:spf-email/sender-policy-framework] Bulk senders (5000+ emails per day) are required to have SPF, DKIM, and DMARC setup for their domains.
